diff --git a/guidelines.yaml b/guidelines.yaml
new file mode 100644
index 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000..5d69f1093def64aabe41440a1e03f1be63ee4a5d
--- /dev/null
+++ b/guidelines.yaml
@@ -0,0 +1,1366 @@
+- name: Requirements # Generated from https://docs.flathub.org/docs/for-app-authors/requirements
+  description: |
+    The goal of these requirements is to ensure that the applications hosted on Flathub are safe to use and integrate well in the desktop experience.
+  items:
+    - name: Inclusion policy
+      description: |
+        Each application is evaluated on a case-by-case basis and if you are unsure whether it fits the guidelines, please feel free to ask via GitHub issues or in the Flathub Matrix room.
+
+        Flathub aims to provide a curated collection of high-quality, sandboxed graphical desktop applications that seamlessly integrate with the Linux desktop environment and enhance the user experience.
+
+        This defines specific policies for submission and inclusion, and applies to all submissions that are (were) submitted or included after the policy was documented, for as long as they remain on Flathub.
+
+        Submissions are accepted at the discretion of the reviewers and are liable to be removed even after they are included, if it is found to violate any policy. They must also comply with Flathub's Terms Of Service.
+
+        These policies may evolve over time, but new policies will not be retroactively applied to submissions predating the introduction of the policy.
+
+        Exceptions may be granted in at our discretion in specific cases.
+      items:
+        - name: Impermissible submissions
+          description: |
+            Submissions must demonstrate sufficient functional scope, user-facing value, desktop integration and functionality and justify distribution.
+
+            The following non-exhaustive categories of submissions will not be accepted.
+          items:
+            - name: Submission is fully functional and has no easily visible issues at the time of submission.
+            - name: Submission is not a console-only software (exceptions may be given to Flatpak or Flathub related tooling).
+            - name:
+                Submission does not offer only minimal functionality such as simple scripts, single or simple sources, or exist
+                as a thin wrapper or launcher around other tools.
+            - name:
+                Submission is not a simple web wrapper application that embeds local or remote content in a web engine without
+                significant polish, functionality, or meaningful desktop integration.
+            - name: Submission is not a shell, window manager, or desktop environment extension.
+            - name: Submission is not a tray-only application that operates exclusively as a tray applet.
+            - name: Submission is not a system utility that is generally used on the host.
+            - name:
+                Submission does not function only in highly specific environments such as requiring a particular desktop environment
+                or distribution (exceptions considered case by case, e.g. a desktop settings application).
+            - name:
+                Submission does not rely on host components or complicated post-installation setups for core functionality (exceptions
+                considered case by case).
+            - name:
+                Submission is not a development tool, file manager, terminal, or IDE with a broad scope unsuited to the Flatpak
+                sandbox — unless officially submitted by upstream developers or upstream has explicitly committed to supporting
+                Flatpak.
+            - name:
+                Submission is not a duplicate of an existing application differing only in framework or toolkit, nor a fork
+                with minimal changes in terms of functionality, content, visuals, or user experience.
+            - name:
+                Submission does not conflict with an existing Flatpak provided by the upstream author or developers outside
+                of Flathub.
+            - name:
+                Submission is not Windows software using Wine, nor any other software that is not native to the Linux desktop
+                and uses an emulation or translation layer — unless submitted officially by upstream with intent to maintain it
+                in an official capacity.
+        - name: End-of-life dependency policy
+          description: |
+            Submissions must not depend on end-of-life software components.
+          items:
+            - name: Submission does not use an end-of-life runtime, extension, or baseapp.
+            - name:
+                Submission does not use high-risk, end-of-life software (e.g. OpenSSL 1.x, Python 2, Qt5 WebKit) while requesting
+                the network or any other invasive permissions.
+            - name:
+                The main application itself is not end-of-life — unless the submitter can demonstrate their ability to maintain
+                it for the foreseeable future and perform runtime upgrades.
+        - name: Software design and distribution policy
+          description: |
+            Applications that include insecure or harmful design choices, such as disabling or bypassing security mechanisms, using insecure cryptographic practices, exposing or accessing sensitive information, or shipping overly permissive configurations will not be accepted.
+
+            Submissions that employ unethical, manipulative, or exploitative design patterns will also be rejected. Applications promoting gambling or games of chance involving real-world money are not permitted.
+
+            Projects must demonstrate reasonable structure, organization, maintainability, and be distributed in a verifiable manner. Open source and source-available projects must follow established conventions of their respective ecosystem.
+          items:
+            - name:
+                Submission does not include insecure or harmful design choices (e.g. disabling or bypassing security mechanisms,
+                insecure cryptographic practices, exposing or accessing sensitive information, overly permissive configurations).
+            - name: Submission does not employ unethical, manipulative, or exploitative design patterns.
+            - name: Submission does not promote gambling or games of chance involving real-world money.
+            - name:
+                Project demonstrates reasonable structure, organization, maintainability, and is distributed in a verifiable
+                manner.
+            - name: Open source and source-available projects follow established conventions of their respective ecosystem.
+        - name: Insufficient development history
+          description: |
+            Submissions must demonstrate a meaningful history of development or existence, evidence of real-world use and a clear commitment to ongoing maintenance.
+
+            Exceptions may be granted on a case by case basis.
+          items:
+            - name: Submission demonstrates a meaningful history of development or existence.
+            - name: Submission shows evidence of real-world use.
+            - name: Submission shows a clear commitment to ongoing maintenance.
+            - name:
+                For source-available projects, there is a sustained commit history and standard release practices such as tagged
+                versions.
+            - name: Application has existed for more than a very short period of time.
+        - name: Extensions or BaseApps
+          description: |
+            Flatpak extensions that add support for new languages, language specific tooling etc. or BaseApps will need a clear use case defined and prospective users to be accepted.
+          items:
+            - name: Extension or BaseApp has a clear use case defined and prospective users identified.
+            - name:
+                BaseApp or Extension is built against a runtime that provides a stable ABI and performs ABI checks as part of
+                their releases.
+            - name: BaseApp or Extension itself maintains a stable ABI in a given branch.
+            - name:
+                BaseApp or Extension does not depend on or use any private ABI from the runtime for its contents (extensions
+                providing themes etc. may be exempt).
+        - name: Trust and history
+          description: |
+            Submission decisions may take a submitter's prior conduct into account.
+          items:
+            - name: Submitter does not have a pattern of policy violations.
+            - name: Submitter has not exhibited uncooperative behaviour.
+            - name: Submitter does not have multiple abandoned or poorly maintained apps.
+            - name: Submitter has not engaged in misleading practices.
+            - name: Submitter has not failed to address security and compliance issues in the past.
+        - name: Misleading, malicious or illegal submissions
+          description: |
+            In most cases such submissions are liable to be outright rejected or removed from the store.
+          items:
+            - name: Submission does not impersonate another project, vendor, or person.
+            - name: Submission does not engage in or encourage unlawful activities.
+            - name: Submission does not provide false or misleading information or functionality.
+            - name: Submission does not attempt to deceive users or violate any laws, trademarks, or copyrights.
+            - name: Submission does not act in a malicious manner and does not contain malicious code.
+        - name: Generative AI policy
+          description: |
+            This policy applies to both the application being submitted to Flathub and the Flathub submission itself, including the manifest, metadata, patches, build scripts, and pull request. For the purpose of this policy, "applications" include Flatpak apps, BaseApps, extensions, runtimes and any other artifacts that can be produced by flatpak-builder.
+
+            Repeatedly violating these policies may result in a permanent ban from future submissions and activities. Exceptions may be granted for mature, well-maintained projects.
+          items:
+            - name: Submission pull request was not generated, opened, or automated using AI tools or agents.
+            - name: Review comments, replies, and descriptions on the PR are not LLM-generated.
+            - name: No review has been requested from AI tools in the submission PR (e.g. automated Copilot reviews are disabled).
+            - name: Application does not contain AI-generated or AI-assisted code, documentation, or any other content.
+            - name:
+                Submission does not contain unauthorised copyrighted material, license-incompatible, or ethically questionable
+                code.
+    - name: Application ID
+      description: |
+        Please choose the ID carefully and don't hesitate to ask the reviewers for help as it will determine the type of verification method available, if any.
+
+        If it needs to be renamed at any point, the application needs to be resubmitted.
+
+        The application ID is a constant and unique identifier of the application consisting of the reverse-DNS format {tld}.{vendor}.{product}.
+
+        The components of the ID are the substrings obtained by splitting it at each dot.
+
+        Demangling an ID or any of its components means removing any leading underscore (_) and converting any other underscore (_) to a dash (-).
+
+        The domain from the ID is determined by reversing its components and demangling them to form a FQDN, which is then matched against PSL. If a match is not found in PSL, all components except the last from the previous final form are taken as the domain.
+      items:
+        - name: ID format rules
+          description: |
+            The following rules must be followed when creating application IDs.
+          items:
+            - name: ID does not exceed 255 characters and has at least 3 components (and no more than 5 components).
+            - name: Each component contains only the characters [A-Z][a-z][0-9]_; a dash (-) is only used in the last component.
+            - name:
+                The domain portion is in lowercase and converts dash (-) to underscore (_); any component with an initial digit
+                is prefixed with an underscore.
+            - name: The ID does not end in generic terms like .desktop, .app, or .linux.
+            - name: The ID exactly matches the ID tag in the Metainfo file.
+            - name:
+                Applications hosted on github.com, gitlab.com, codeberg.org, framagit.org use io.github., io.gitlab., page.codeberg.,
+                io.frama. prefixes respectively and have at least 4 components.
+            - name:
+                com.github., com.gitlab., org.codeberg., org.framagit. prefixes are reserved for official projects of the code
+                hosting platform (not used by third-party submissions).
+            - name: Applications hosted on Sourceforge use io.sourceforge. or net.sourceforge. prefixes.
+        - name: Control over domain or repository
+          description: |
+            The domain must be directly related to the project or the application being submitted and the author or the developer or the project must have control over the domain.
+          items:
+            - name: The domain is directly related to the project or application being submitted.
+            - name: The author, developer, or project has control over the domain.
+            - name: The corresponding URL is reachable over HTTPS (or an exception has been granted after manual checking).
+            - name: If required, a verification token has been placed under https://{domain name}/.well-known/org.flathub.VerifiedApps.txt.
+            - name:
+                There is visible proof on the webpage linking the application, developer, or project to the domain calculated
+                from the ID (preferable).
+        - name: Code hosting
+          description: |
+            A repository URL (or project URL) is calculated for code hosting IDs by using the domain and by taking the last component of the ID as-is (except when the last component starts with a leading underscore and then a digit, in which case following Appstream conventions, the leading underscore is stripped from that component).
+          items:
+            - name:
+                For code-hosting IDs, the username or repository name portion does not contain '.' (since that serves as a component
+                delimiter).
+            - name:
+                The repository URL calculated from the code hosting ID is reachable (or an exception has been granted after
+                manual checking).
+            - name: Case sensitivity of the hosting platform's namespace (e.g. GitLab) has been respected in the ID.
+        - name: Protected ID prefixes
+          description: |
+            Certain ID prefixes are restricted and reserved for specific projects.
+          items:
+            - name: org.gnome. is only used by apps in the official allow-list (restriction applies to the toplevel namespace).
+            - name: org.kde. is only used for projects hosted in a group on KDE Invent.
+            - name: com.system76. is only used for projects hosted in the pop-os organization on GitHub.
+        - name: Extensions and BaseApps
+          description: |
+            BaseApps must have BaseApp as the last component of the Flatpak ID and for the rest of the ID, the above rules apply.
+
+            Flatpak extensions must prefix their ID with the extension point ID, which is either defined in one of the runtimes or in an app. If the extension point is defined in an app, it must use the app's ID as a prefix. They are exempt from the domain control rules.
+          items:
+            - name: BaseApp submissions have "BaseApp" as the last component of the Flatpak ID.
+            - name:
+                Flatpak extensions are prefixed with the extension point ID (defined in a runtime or app); if defined in an
+                app, the app's ID is used as the prefix.
+        - name: Renaming Flatpak ID
+          description: |
+            Flatpak ID renames are reviewed and accepted on a conservative basis provided justified reasons for the rename are provided.
+
+            Exceptions may be considered on a case by case basis.
+          items:
+            - name: Rename request changes the domain portion of the Flatpak ID.
+            - name: Rename request that changes the domain portion includes a clear intention to verify the new ID.
+            - name: Rename was not requested immediately after the initial submission was accepted.
+            - name: Rename requests have not been made frequently for this application.
+    - name: License
+      description: |
+        All content hosted on Flathub must allow legal redistribution, and the license must be correctly specified in the app's MetaInfo file.
+
+        Non-redistributable sources must use extra-data source type. Any part of the application such as the name or icon must not violate any trademarks and must be distinct.
+      items:
+        - name: License allows legal redistribution of all content hosted on Flathub.
+          description: null
+          items: null
+        - name: License is correctly declared in the MetaInfo file and matches the license information available in the source.
+          description: null
+          items: null
+        - name: Non-redistributable sources use the extra-data source type.
+          description: null
+          items: null
+        - name: No part of the application (name, icon, etc.) violates any trademarks; all such parts are distinct.
+          description: null
+          items: null
+        - name: License of contents in Flathub repository
+          description: |
+            The use of a specific license is not mandated or required, and including a license in the repository is optional. However, submitters and maintainers may choose to apply a license if desired.
+
+            In the absence of an explicit license, contributors will retain their respective copyrights over the contents of the repository.
+          items:
+            - name:
+                Repository does not use a restrictive license for the manifest or build scripts (permissive licenses such as
+                MIT, 0BSD, or the Unlicense are recommended).
+            - name:
+                If included, license file is part of the pull request, or individual files are annotated with a license at the
+                top level.
+        - name: Installing license files
+          description: |
+            Application maintainers and submitters must ensure that license files for each module in the Flatpak manifest is installed to $FLATPAK_DEST/share/licenses/$FLATPAK_ID.
+
+            Recent versions of Flatpak builder can do this automatically for common license file names as long as the license files are in the root of the source directory. If the license file is not being automatically installed, it must be manually installed.
+          items:
+            - name:
+                License files for each module in the Flatpak manifest are installed to $FLATPAK_DEST/share/licenses/$FLATPAK_ID
+                (either automatically by Flatpak builder or manually via install/post-install commands).
+    - name: Permissions
+      description: |
+        Static permissions must be kept to an absolute minimum. Applications should rely on XDG Portals and follow established XDG standards wherever possible.
+
+        When a suitable XDG portal exists, is supported across the ecosystem, and covers the application's use case, or can be implemented in the application itself — using the portal becomes mandatory instead of static permissions. Exceptions to this can be allowed on a case by case basis but note that using niche or unmaintained setups or dependencies may not count as grounds for allowing an exception.
+      items:
+        - name: Static permissions are kept to an absolute minimum.
+          description: null
+          items: null
+        - name: Application relies on XDG Portals and follows established XDG standards wherever possible.
+          description: null
+          items: null
+        - name:
+            Where a suitable XDG portal exists, is supported across the ecosystem, and covers the use case (or can be implemented
+            in the application), the portal is used instead of static permissions.
+          description: null
+          items: null
+    - name: No network access during build
+      description: |
+        All dependencies needed to build and run the application must be present in the manifest as sources with publicly accessible URLs or must be included as local sources in the submission pull request. Binary or precompiled files must not be present in the submission pull request.
+
+        There is no network access during the build process. This means using --share=network inside build-args will not work.
+      items:
+        - name:
+            All dependencies needed to build and run the application are present in the manifest as sources with publicly
+            accessible URLs, or are included as local sources in the submission PR.
+          description: null
+          items: null
+        - name: No binary or precompiled files are present in the submission pull request.
+          description: null
+          items: null
+        - name: The manifest does not use --share=network inside build-args.
+          description: null
+          items: null
+    - name: Building from source
+      description: |
+        All source available submissions must be built entirely from source code. This requirement applies to the main application component defined in the manifest, as well as any runtime dependencies included in the manifest.
+
+        Exceptions may be granted to well-known vendors on a case-by-case basis, for example where the necessary tooling to perform an offline source build is not available. However, the use of niche tooling or uncommon build setups may not constitute grounds for an exception.
+      items:
+        - name: The main application component is built entirely from source code.
+          description: null
+          items: null
+        - name: All runtime dependencies included in the manifest are built entirely from source code.
+          description: null
+          items: null
+    - name: Localisation policy
+      description: |
+        All submissions must include a complete English localisation for their user interface, user-facing content, desktop file, metainfo and any readme or documentation. Low quality, automated or machine-generated or mixed translations cannot be used.
+
+        This requirement does not apply if the submission is inherently region-specific, for example government or banking applications. Furthermore, exceptions can be made for new submissions, if the author's native language is not English and they were unable to find contributors to help in the English localisation.
+      items:
+        - name: Submission includes a complete English localisation for the user interface.
+          description: null
+          items: null
+        - name: Submission includes a complete English localisation for user-facing content.
+          description: null
+          items: null
+        - name: Submission includes a complete English localisation for the desktop file, metainfo, and any readme or documentation.
+          description: null
+          items: null
+        - name: Translations are not low quality, automated, machine-generated, or mixed.
+          description: null
+          items: null
+        - name:
+            If the submission is available only in one or more non-English locales, this is stated in its metadata using description
+            notes.
+          description: null
+          items: null
+    - name: Patches
+      description: |
+        Submissions must aim to distribute the application with minimal modifications and must closely follow the upstream source.
+      items:
+        - name: Submission distributes the application with minimal modifications and closely follows the upstream source.
+          description: null
+          items: null
+        - name: All patches required for the modifications are included in the submission along with the manifest.
+          description: null
+          items: null
+    - name: Stable releases
+      description: |
+        The Flathub stable repository is dedicated to hosting only stable software. The Flathub beta repository can be used to publish beta software, though it will not be listed on the website and users must be manually migrated if switched to the stable repo later.
+
+        New submissions will not be accepted for the Flathub beta repository.
+      items:
+        - name: Submission targets the Flathub stable repository and contains only stable software.
+          description: null
+          items: null
+        - name: Submission is not a nightly release, development snapshot, or software requiring daily updates.
+          description: null
+          items: null
+        - name: Submission is not a new submission to the Flathub beta repository.
+          description: null
+          items: null
+    - name: Required files
+      description: |
+        Under no circumstances should source code nor build artifacts be included in the submission. Flathub is not intended to host application source code nor binaries, including that of any dependencies.
+
+        The following files must be included in the submission.
+      items:
+        - name: No application source code is included in the submission.
+          description: null
+          items: null
+        - name: No build artifacts (including dependency binaries) are included in the submission.
+          description: null
+          items: null
+        - name: Manifest
+          description: |
+            The application manifest must be at the top level and named after the application ID with the extension .json, .yml or .yaml depending on whether it is a JSON or YAML file.
+
+            The runtime(s) used in the manifest must be hosted on Flathub and must be the latest version at that time of submission.
+          items:
+            - name: The application manifest is at the top level of the submission.
+            - name: The manifest is named after the application ID, with extension .json, .yml, or .yaml as appropriate.
+            - name: The runtime(s) used in the manifest are hosted on Flathub.
+            - name: The runtime(s) used in the manifest are the latest version at the time of submission.
+        - name: Flatpak builder Manifest Style Guide
+          description: |
+            The style guide ensures manifests are readable, maintainable and has a logical meaning and flow.
+          items:
+            - name: JSON manifest style
+              description: |
+                Style rules for JSON manifests.
+              items:
+                - name:
+                    'Manifest is valid JSON per RFC 7159 (non-standard features such as comments use "//": or "x-comment": keys,
+                    or YAML manifests are used instead).'
+                  description: null
+                  items: null
+                - name: Indentation is 4 tabs with LF line endings.
+                  description: null
+                  items: null
+                - name: Encoding is UTF-8.
+                  description: null
+                  items: null
+                - name: File has a trailing newline.
+                  description: null
+                  items: null
+                - name: Double quotes are used for all keys and string values.
+                  description: null
+                  items: null
+                - name: No trailing commas are used.
+                  description: null
+                  items: null
+            - name: YAML manifest style
+              description: |
+                Style rules for YAML manifests.
+              items:
+                - name: Manifest is valid YAML.
+                  description: null
+                  items: null
+                - name: Indentation is 2 spaces with LF line endings.
+                  description: null
+                  items: null
+                - name: Encoding is UTF-8.
+                  description: null
+                  items: null
+                - name: File has a trailing newline.
+                  description: null
+                  items: null
+                - name: Child elements are always indented.
+                  description: null
+                  items: null
+                - name: Blank lines are inserted between modules.
+                  description: null
+                  items: null
+                - name: Values are not vertically aligned.
+                  description: null
+                  items: null
+                - name: List items are indented consistently.
+                  description: null
+                  items: null
+                - name: Strings remain unquoted unless quoting is required.
+                  description: null
+                  items: null
+            - name: Logical ordering of keys
+              description: |
+                Manifest properties must be ordered logically and not alphabetically. Expected order at the top level: id/app-id, runtime, runtime-version, sdk, branch/default-branch, build-runtime/build-extension, separate-locales, appstream-compose, command, base, base-version, base-extensions, inherit-extensions, sdk-extensions, inherit-sdk-extensions, platform-extensions, add-extensions, add-build-extensions, rename-desktop-file, rename-appdata-file, rename-mime-file, rename-mime-icons, rename-icon, copy-icon, finish-args, cleanup, cleanup-commands, build-options, modules. Within a module: name, buildsystem, build-options, make-args, make-install-args, rm-configure, no-autogen, no-parallel-make, subdir, builddir, run-tests, license-files, only-arches/skip-arches, config-opts/build-commands, post-install, cleanup, sources. Within a source: type, url/path/paths/commands/contents, mirror-urls, disable-http-decompression, archive-type, sha/commit/tag/(tag then commit), size, dest/dest-filename/filename, strip-components/disable-submodules/disable-lfs/disable-shallow-clone, only-arches/skip-arches, x-checker-data.
+              items:
+                - name: Top-level manifest properties are ordered logically (not alphabetically) per the documented order.
+                  description: null
+                  items: null
+                - name: Module properties are ordered logically (not alphabetically) per the documented order.
+                  description: null
+                  items: null
+                - name: Source properties are ordered logically (not alphabetically) per the documented order.
+                  description: null
+                  items: null
+        - name: Creating submanifests
+          description: |
+            Sub-manifests with sources must only be created when they are generated using an external tooling or in an automatic manner, otherwise, everything must be in the main manifest.
+          items:
+            - name:
+                Sub-manifests with sources only exist where they are generated by external tooling or in an automatic manner;
+                otherwise everything is in the main manifest.
+        - name: flathub.json
+          description: |
+            Flathub builds on both x86_64 and aarch64 by default. If the application is supported on only one architecture, please include a flathub.json file in the submission pull request with the proper contents.
+          items:
+            - name:
+                If the application supports only one of x86_64 or aarch64, a flathub.json file with the proper contents is included
+                in the submission.
+            - name: The flathub.json file resides in the top-level root, next to the Flatpak manifest.
+        - name: Dependency manifest
+          description: |
+            There is no network access during the build process so all dependencies used by the application must be supplied in the specified in the manifest as sources with publicly accessible URLs so that they can be downloaded before the build starts.
+
+            There is a community provided set of tools that can be used to generate dependency manifests for npm, yarn, cargo, pip etc.
+          items:
+            - name: All dependencies are supplied in the manifest as sources with publicly accessible URLs.
+            - name: Generated dependency manifests (for npm, yarn, cargo, pip, etc.) are included in the submission.
+    - name: Required metadata
+      description: |
+        Applications must provide the following metadata typically as part of their source code.
+
+        These metadata files must be integrated in the upstream project. Please do not include a copy in the submission pull request unless it is using an extra-data source for the application.
+      items:
+        - name:
+            Required metadata files are integrated in the upstream project (not copied into the submission PR), unless the
+            application uses an extra-data source.
+          description: null
+          items: null
+        - name: Name and Icon
+          description: |
+            The application name and icon as presented to the Flathub website and to users must be distinct and must not violate any trademarks.
+
+            Official affiliation must not be implied by using a vendor's name in the application name or icon unless the application is actually part of that vendor's project.
+
+            Icons must be sufficiently distinct to convey the project's own identity and prevent any risk of user confusion.
+
+            Vendor-specific policies (e.g. GNOME, COSMIC) must also be respected where applicable.
+          items:
