+- name: Quality guidelines # Generated from https://docs.flathub.org/docs/for-app-authors/metainfo-guidelines/quality-guidelines
+  description: |
+    The following guidelines are not required for submission to Flathub, but are best practices recommended and considered for curation and promotion. They are designed to help your app and Flathub itself appear in the best light to users. The guidelines may change over time based on developer and user feedback.
+
+    The term "must" in these guidelines is used in the context of considering whether an app passes the app listing quality checks. Apps that do not follow these guidelines may still be published on Flathub.
+
+    Passing the quality checks enhances an application's visibility on the Flathub homepage. Applications that meet all the checks can be featured prominently on the weekly banner and "App of the Day" highlights on a rotational basis. The more guidelines an application meets, the higher its chances of being featured in the trending section of flathub.org.
+  items:
+    - name: General
+      description: |
+        General quality criteria that apply across the application listing.
+      items:
+        - name: No trademark violations
+          description: |
+            Please see the policy in the requirements section.
+          items:
+            - name: Application name, icon, and other listing elements do not violate any trademarks (per the requirements policy).
+        - name: Runtime not end-of-life
+          description: |
+            Your app must target a runtime that is not end-of-life (EOL). This means you should not use deprecated or obsolete runtimes, as they may not receive security updates or support.
+
+            Check Runtimes for runtime support periods and expected eol dates.
+          items:
+            - name: Application targets a runtime that is not end-of-life.
+        - name: Managed by app author
+          description: |
+            Use Flathub verification to indicate that you are the author of the app and that you are managing the app on Flathub.
+          items:
+            - name: Application is verified on Flathub by its author/maintainer.
+    - name: Brand colors
+      description: |
+        Brand colors are used by Flathub and native app store clients on banners, app pages, etc.
+      items:
+        - name: Has primary brand colors
+          description: |
+            Apps should set two primary brand colors, light and dark.
+          items:
+            - name: <branding> declares a primary <color> for both light and dark variants.
+        - name: Good brand colors
+          description: |
+            Brand colors are often used as a background behind the app icon, so make sure the colors are not too similar to the app icon in order to ensure good contrast.
+
+            In most cases the dark variant should be a darker, more muted version of the light brand color. Do not use the same color for the dark and light variants.
+
+            Brand colors should be colorful — avoid white (or very light grays) and black (or very dark grays).
+
+            A good starting point is a lighter/darker version of the primary icon color or a complementary color that pairs well with it. It's recommended to consider brand colors an extension of the app icon, and have the icon designer choose them.
+          items:
+            - name: Brand colors have good contrast with the app icon (the icon is clearly distinguishable on the brand color background).
+            - name:
+                Dark variant is a darker, more muted version of the light brand color (not a light color, not the same as the
+                light variant).
+            - name: Brand colors are colorful (not near-white/near-black grays).
+            - name: Brand colors complement or extend the app icon.
+    - name: App Icon
+      description: |
+        Quality criteria for the application icon.
+      items:
+        - name: Icon size
+          description: |
+            The icon should be SVG, or a PNG with a size greater or equal to 256x256 pixels. It has to be square.
+          items:
+            - name: Icon is SVG or a square PNG of 256x256 pixels or larger.
+        - name: Reasonable footprint
+          description: |
+            The icon shouldn't fill too much or too little of the canvas. Avoid filling the entire canvas and having the icon touch the edges of the canvas (except with small protruding elements). Similarly, avoid thin shapes that are hard to see.
+          items:
+            - name: Icon does not fill the entire canvas or touch the canvas edges (small protrusions excepted).
+            - name: Icon is not so thin or sparse that it's hard to see.
+        - name: Good contrast
+          description: |
+            The icon should have good contrast on dark and light backgrounds. In particular, avoid single-color glyphs and the like since they can be very hard to see if the background color is similar. Dark colors near the edges are also a problem since shadows don't help much with contrast on dark backgrounds.
+          items:
+            - name: Icon has good contrast on both light and dark backgrounds.
+            - name: Icon is not a single-color glyph and avoids dark colors near its edges.
+        - name: Not too much or too little detail
+          description: |
+            The icon should be recognizable in small sizes. Avoid too many tiny details and small text, and generally try and match other well-executed app icons in terms of complexity. Icons should also be complex enough to be recognizable, e.g. a flat single-colored symbol is too simple.
+          items:
+            - name: Icon is recognizable at small sizes (no tiny details, no small text).
+            - name: Icon is complex enough to be recognizable (not a flat, single-colored symbol).
+        - name: No baked-in shadows
+          description: |
+            The icon should not have any baked-in shadows or glows. Both the Flathub website and native stores apply a shadow to all icons, so baked-in shadows result in double shadows or other glitches.
+          items:
+            - name: Icon has no baked-in shadows or glows.
+        - name: In line with contemporary styles
+          description: |
+            The icon should be somewhat in line with the contemporary icon styles (i.e. not look like it hasn't been updated in decades). The GNOME and KDE app icon guidelines are examples of the kind of style your icon should align with.
+
+            In some cases, it can make sense for the icon to align with the visuals of the app, rather than contemporary icon styles (especially relevant for games). This can be accommodated by embedding the custom style icon in one of the grid shapes, e.g. a square or circle. This way the unique style is preserved, but the icon's size and shape are in line with other apps.
+          items:
+            - name:
+                Icon style is in line with contemporary app icon styles (e.g. follows GNOME/KDE icon guidelines), or a custom-style
+                icon (e.g. for games) is embedded into a standard grid shape.
+    - name: App Name
+      description: |
+        Quality criteria for the application name.
+      items:
+        - name: Not too long
+          description: |
+            The name should ideally be no longer than 15 characters, and must be shorter than 20 characters.
+          items:
+            - name: Application name is shorter than 20 characters (ideally no longer than 15).
+        - name: Just the name
+          description: |
+            The name should be just a short name, without any additional information. For example, don't append what the app does or is used for to the name; use the summary to provide this information instead.
+
+            If the app is distinct among different versions of your app on Flathub (e.g. Firefox Beta versus the standard Firefox), then using the full name including the edition may be acceptable.
+          items:
+            - name:
+                Application name is just the short name, without descriptive tagline or parenthetical (an edition suffix like
+                "Beta" is acceptable when distinguishing variants).
+        - name: No weird formatting
+          description: |
+            App names should avoid nonstandard formatting and punctuation. For example, avoid all-lowercase, all-uppercase, camel/pascal case, and punctuation like dashes or periods.
+
+            Cases where the formatting is part of an established brand may be exempt (e.g. VLC).
+          items:
+            - name:
+                Application name avoids nonstandard formatting (no all-lowercase, all-uppercase, camel/pascal case, or punctuation
+                like dashes/periods), unless the formatting is part of an established brand.
+    - name: Summary
+      description: |
+        Quality criteria for the application summary.
+      items:
+        - name: Not too long
+          description: |
+            The summary should ideally be between 10 and 25 characters, and no longer than 35 characters.
+          items:
+            - name: Summary is no longer than 35 characters (ideally between 10 and 25).
+        - name: Not technical
+          description: |
+            The summary should be understandable by a non-technical person, and not contain any technical terms. Don't mention the toolkit, programming language, or other implementation details that would not be relevant to a non-developer and explain what the app does for people instead. Don't duplicate metadata that's already available in a different form, such as the license, e.g. by mentioning that the app is "free and open source". Avoid generic nouns like "app", "tool", or "client".
+          items:
+            - name: Summary is understandable by a non-technical person and contains no technical terms (toolkit, language, etc.).
+            - name: Summary does not duplicate metadata available elsewhere (e.g. license, "free and open source").
+            - name: Summary avoids generic nouns like "app", "tool", or "client".
+        - name: No weird formatting
+          description: |
+            The summary should not have any weird formatting or punctuation. It should use sentence case, rather than title case. It shouldn't end with a full stop.
+          items:
+            - name: Summary uses sentence case (not title case).
+            - name: Summary does not end with a full stop and has no unusual formatting/punctuation.
+        - name: Don't repeat the name
+          description: |
+            The summary is usually shown next to the app name, so repeating the name looks bad.
+          items:
+            - name: Summary does not repeat the application name.
+        - name: Don't start with an article
+          description: |
+            Starting summaries with an article is almost always unnecessary. Instead, either omit the article or ideally phrase it in the imperative with a verb.
+          items:
+            - name: Summary does not start with an article (a/an/the); ideally it is phrased imperatively with a verb.
+    - name: Description
+      description: |
+        Quality criteria for the application description.
+      items:
+        - name: Don't repeat the summary
+          description: |
+            The description should not just repeat or rephrase the summary. The summary is a kind of slogan or advertisement for the app, while the description should go into more detail about the purpose of the app, which features it has, and what makes it unique.
+          items:
+            - name:
+                Description does not just repeat or rephrase the summary; it goes into detail about purpose, features, and what
+                makes the app unique.
+        - name: Not too short
+          description: |
+            The description should be substantially longer than the summary. Something like 3-6 lines of text at default line widths (around 70 characters) is a good length for most apps, for very large apps up to about 10 lines.
+          items:
+            - name:
+                Description is substantially longer than the summary (roughly 3-6 lines at ~70 char width for most apps, up
+                to 10 for large apps).
+        - name: No super long lists
+          description: |
+            Avoid feature lists with more than 10 items, they are difficult to scan and make the app store listing unwieldy. Instead, try to group points or use paragraphs instead of bullet points.
+          items:
+            - name: Description does not contain feature lists with more than 10 items (points are grouped or expressed as paragraphs).
+    - name: Screenshots
+      description: |
+        Quality criteria for application screenshots.
+      items:
+        - name: At least one screenshot
+          description: |
+            Apps should have at least one screenshot in English. For medium-complexity apps, 3-6 is a good range, for very large apps with lots of screens 6-10 is appropriate. More than 10 is probably too many.
+
+            Your best screenshot should be in the first position because it will be the first thing a user sees when viewing your app on Flathub. We might also use this in other places, such as featured banners, so make sure it's a good one.
+          items:
+            - name: App has at least one screenshot in English (medium apps 3-6, large apps 6-10, no more than ~10).
+            - name:
+                The best screenshot is placed first, since it is the first one a user sees and may also be used in featured
+                banners.
+        - name: Tag screenshots with the correct language
+          description: |
+            Screenshots should be tagged with the language they are in. For example, if you have a screenshot of the app in German, tag it with xml:lang="de".
+          items:
+            - name: Localised screenshots are tagged with the correct xml:lang attribute matching the language shown.
+        - name: Just the app window
+          description: |
+            Use the "window screenshot" feature in your native system screenshot tool to get just the app window and its shadow. Do not include the wallpaper behind the app or even the entire desktop. Do not edit the screenshot, crop it, add text, or include promotional graphics.
+          items:
+            - name:
+                Screenshots show just the app window and its shadow (no wallpaper/desktop, no editing/cropping/added text/promotional
+                graphics).
+        - name: Take screenshots on Linux
+          description: |
+            Do not use screenshots taken on other platforms, especially if it's immediately obvious from window controls and the like.
+          items:
+            - name:
+                Screenshots are taken on Linux (no screenshots from other platforms where it would be obvious from window controls
+                etc.).
+        - name: Default settings
+          description: |
+            Use the platform default configuration for all settings that affect screenshots, including window controls, interface font, large text, high contrast, dark style, accent color, and so on. Having some screenshots to show off that e.g. dark style is supported is fine, but these should not be the only screenshots.
+          items:
+            - name:
+                Screenshots use the platform default configuration (default window controls, interface font, no large text/high
+                contrast, etc.).
+            - name: If dark style or similar variations are showcased, they are not the only screenshots provided.
+        - name: Include window shadow and rounded corners
+          description: |
+            Screenshots must include the native decoration such as any title bar, window shadows, and rounded corners. App stores do not add a shadow after the fact, and without one, screenshots can look glitchy or have low contrast depending on the background. Apps that are always fullscreen (such as most games) are exempt from this, but in these cases, all screenshots must be fullscreen. Do not use a mix of windowed and fullscreen screenshots.
+
+            Don't maximize your app window when taking screenshots, since this will remove the shadow and rounding.
+          items:
+            - name:
+                Screenshots include native window decoration (title bar, window shadow, rounded corners) and the window is not
+                maximised.
+            - name: For always-fullscreen apps (e.g. games), all screenshots are fullscreen and not mixed with windowed screenshots.
+        - name: Reasonable window size
+          description: |
+            In order to ensure that text and interface elements are visible scaled down in the app store UI the window size should be 1000x700 pixels or smaller (2000x1400 for HiDPI).
+          items:
+            - name: Screenshot window size is 1000x700 pixels or smaller (2000x1400 for HiDPI).
+        - name: Image captions
+          description: |
+            Every screenshot should have a caption briefly describing it. Captions should only be one sentence and not end with a full stop. Don't start them with a number.
+          items:
+            - name: Every screenshot has a <caption>.
+            - name: Captions are a single sentence, don't end with a full stop, and don't start with a number.
+        - name: Good content
+          description: |
+            Screenshots of apps that display content (media viewers, notes apps, chat, social media, and the like) should not show empty states or ugly content. Take some time to select high-quality content, it makes all the difference for screenshots.
+          items:
+            - name: Screenshots of content-displaying apps show curated, high-quality content (no empty states or ugly content).
+        - name: Up to date
+          description: |
+            Screenshots should reflect the current state of the app's interface, not some previous version. If an app update makes visible changes to the interface, screenshots should be updated at the same time.
+
+            This also applies to changes in the environment's default window decoration layout.
+          items:
+            - name: Screenshots reflect the current state of the app's interface and the current default window decoration layout.
+    - name: Release Notes
+      description: |
+        Quality criteria for release notes.
+      items:
+        - name: Release notes for every release
+          description: |
+            Make sure all your releases have release notes, even minor ones.
+          items:
+            - name: Every release has release notes, including minor ones.
+        - name: Short but informative
+          description: |
+            Release notes should not be too long, and focus on briefly explaining what changed from a user perspective. 2-3 sentences for medium-sized releases is a good length. For larger releases, avoid endless bullet point lists and rather go with a few paragraphs or a shorter summarized list instead.
+          items:
+            - name:
+                Release notes are short but informative (about 2-3 sentences for medium releases; paragraphs or a summarised
+                list for larger ones, avoiding endless bullet lists).
+        - name: No "bug fixes and performance improvements"
+          description: |
+            Release notes should include some actual information about what changed rather than just a generic boilerplate.
+          items:
+            - name:
+                Release notes contain actual information about what changed (no generic boilerplate like "bug fixes and performance
+                improvements").
+    - name: Age Ratings
+      description: |
+        Quality criteria for age ratings.
+      items:
+        - name: Take easily accessible content into account
+          description: |
+            Apps acting as "readers" or "stores" for external content should take into account what is accessible by just navigating around in the app. If content of a certain type can be arrived at without searching or typing in URLs, the app should be tagged as containing it. For example, an RSS reader that doesn't feature any content can be "All Ages", but the rating for a manga app with pre-configured servers should reflect the content of those default sources.
+
+            Please see the MetaInfo guidelines on how to generate proper age ratings.
+          items:
+            - name:
+                Age ratings for "reader" or "store" apps reflect the content reachable just by navigating in the app (not only
+                the empty/default state).

